The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Know your Foggy City Orphan
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                          Know your Foggy City Orphan
          JHINUK MAZUMDAR                          Participants at The Telegraph Know and Grow with Derek quiz, held at Army Public School, Ballygunge, on January 28. Picture by Sanjoy Chattopadhyaya                        
	Do you know which famous English novel was translated as Foggy City Orphan in Chinese, or which part of the human body the formula 2.1.2.3 refers to?         
	For the six school teams that made it to the finals of The Telegraph Know and Grow with Derek quiz contest, held on January 28 at Army Public School, Ballygunge, figuring out the answers  Oliver Twist and the teeth  were all part of a days hard quizzing.         
	National Gems Higher Secondary School, Kalyani Public School and Mahadevi Birla Girls Higher Secondary School were among the six teams, each made up of six students from Class III to VIII.         
	Based on the general knowledge and life skills book Know and Grow with Derek, by quizmaster Derek OBrien, it went beyond the question-answer format, with participants revealing their creative streak as well.         
	In the personality round, the Don Bosco, Park Circus team recited a poem composed by one of its members, Calcutta Boys School sang the Rabindrasangeet Phule phule dhole dhole while Kalyani Public School drew a landscape.                   Students of Calcutta Blind School, Behala, play Holi on February 26 on the school grounds. The kids, four to 10 years old, had fun applying abir on each other. Picture by Bishwarup Dutta      
	While three students of classes III, IV and V from each team battled it out in the first three rounds, those of classes VI, VII and VIII took part in the next three. The Headline round saw the teams identify famous events using a visual clue and the date and come up with headlines for them. Slides required students to identify the two words that would together make a new one.         
	Syed Muztaba Ali, a Class V student of La Martiniere for Boys, found it easy to put together the word bookworm from visuals of a book and a worm. Other rounds included creative, general knowledge and crossword.        
	Don Bosco finished first, with La Martiniere for Boys and Calcutta Boys as the first and second runners-up, respectively. All three received books from Pearson Education, the publisher of Know and Grow with Derek.         
	The quiz, especially the personality and creative rounds, were a pleasant change from the usual pattern of quiz contests, said Bikramaditya Ghosh of Don Bosco.                                                                                                                                                      
